# Custom class

For a date-only value, use `LocalDate`. For a time-only value, use `LocalTime`. For a date with time but lacking the context of an offset-from-UTC or a time zone, use `LocalDateTime`. For a date with time in the context of an offset, use `OffsetDateTime`. For a date with time in the context of a time zone, use `ZonedDateTime`. 

If you *really* want date with an optional time, I would define a class having those two fields, a `LocalDate` with a `LocalTime`, the second being null when omitted. If meant to be immutable, define that class as a [record][1]. 

    record DateWithOptionalTime ( LocalDate date , LocalTime time ) {}

Example usage:

    DateWithOptionalTime x = new DateWithOptionalTime( LocalDate.of( 2024 , Month.JANUARY , 23 ) , LocalTime.of( 12 , 30 ) ) ;

… and:

    DateWithOptionalTime y = new DateWithOptionalTime( LocalDate.of( 2024 , Month.JANUARY , 23 ) , null ) ;

We could add a constructor to verify the date is always supplied (call `Objects.requireNonNull`) while allowing a null time. 

For convenience, add a second constructor taking only the date portion. 

And we could add a `toLocalDateTime` method that returns an `Optional`. If the time-of-day field is null, this method returns an empty `Optional` object. Otherwise, this method instantiates and returns a `LocalDateTime` object. If this method were under extreme demand, you could optimize by caching internally the `LocalDateTime`, but generally I would not bother.

```java
package work.basil.example.datetime;

import java.time.LocalDate;
import java.time.LocalDateTime;
import java.time.LocalTime;
import java.util.Objects;
import java.util.Optional;

public record DateWithOptionalTime( LocalDate date , LocalTime time )
{
    public DateWithOptionalTime ( final LocalDate date , final LocalTime time )
    {
        this.date = Objects.requireNonNull ( date );
        this.time = time;
    }

    public DateWithOptionalTime ( final LocalDate date )
    {
        this ( Objects.requireNonNull ( date ) , null );
    }

    public Optional &lt; LocalDateTime &gt; toLocalDateTime ( )
    {
        if ( Objects.isNull ( this.time ) ) return Optional.empty ( );
        return Optional.of ( LocalDateTime.of ( this.date , this.time ) );
    }
}
```


----------


That said, I would double-check the thinking that led you to this design goal of a date with optional time. 



